{"attack":true,"cited_input_aliases":["A1"],"claim":"The target violates the standard by failing to state a forbidden case that is a concrete observation which could realistically have obtained.","counterexample":null,"grounds":"The standard requires that a historical-mechanism account state forbidden cases that are 'concrete observations which could realistically have obtained (a record, an event, a datable pattern).' The target's forbidden case is 'Mass graves or destruction layers indicating violent conquest by external Sea Peoples rather than internal abandonment or burning by inhabitants.' This is not a concrete observation that could realistically have obtained under the target's own theory; it is a description of evidence that would support a rival theory. A proper forbidden case must be a specific, datable archaeological or textual record that would falsify the target's mechanism of deliberate, coordinated de-urbanization by subordinate groups. For example, a realistic forbidden case would be: 'A preserved Linear B tablet from Pylos dated to the final destruction layer recording a royal decree of forced evacuation, rather than records of resource withholding or work stoppages by local groups.' The target merely contrasts its mechanism with an external invasion scenario, failing to specify what observable, concrete record would be incompatible with its own proposed mechanism of internal, bottom-up resistance.","target_alias":"A1"}